If I had kids right now and I had any idea they're doing anything close to what I would be doing when I was 12, 13 years old, Oh my gosh, I'd be horribly anxious all the time about them. But my mother, when I finally went off to college, I sat her down and I just told her everything I did. I was like, Mom, college is a clean slate. I know my record has been clean since I turned 18, my criminal record. But there's this clean slate and I want to have a clean slate with you. So I sat down and I just shared with her all the different things I'd gotten and how I've been killed a couple of times. And it just went through every story of everything I'd ever done. And she said at the end, She first said, have you been to confession? It was the first thing she said, and I said yes. And then she said, second of all, she said, I hope you appreciate what the Theotokos, what the Mother of God, what Mary has done for you. She has been protecting you this entire time. And she said, I hope you've been appreciative enough. And that was convicting because confession, okay, I went to confession. But, you know, being appreciative for the care and the concern. She was, my mom was pretty much saying, I'm your mother. I could not take care of you during those times. I didn't even know you were doing those stupid things. But the mother of God was obviously very aware. She was obviously caring for you. So she said, make sure you're appreciative to the mother of God for what she's done for you in protecting you. Well, of course, I went through college. maintaining this protection from the mother of God. I didn't even know I was going to be a priest at that point. So there's this real, obviously, sense of humor, but a beautiful understanding of the care and the concern the mother of God has had in my life. And I think when we understand that, especially mothers, my mom will say that she surrendered her motherhood the moment she found out that we were in her womb, the moment she found out that there was a life growing up in her. She said, I surrender my motherhood to the mother of God. It was very much like, I cannot care for this child as much as I want to, but so I surrender the care for the most part to the mother of God. It was a consecration. It was a surrender. It was just this beautiful awareness of her. role and the role of the gift of the mother of God in her life. So quick question on that. So was that a particular devotion that your mom had, or is that just kind of part of the spirituality that you grew up with, this sense of the protection, Mary as a protector and the consecrating of children? The one time she shared with me then, just kind of, I think because she realized that I had put myself in so much danger, just the idea of protection came to her. But the idea of her consecrating us when we were first born, I think it was her own language. It was a real, it was an act of humility kind of to say, you know, especially once my baby's born, I no longer have full control over them. I have for nine months. I can protect this child because they're inside my body. I can protect this child with everything that I am. I can be a mama bear. I can fight. I can protect it. But as soon as the baby's out of my womb, and especially when they get old enough to leave, and I think my mom just kind of went through this whole process, especially with me, her firstborn. So I think it was just a very motherly act, and it was a humility in saying, I cannot. be as motherly as I want to be. And that just came in. And so there was very, I think it just kind of flowed from her piety, you know, and that she desired that. But I do tell people now, and I want to put it as part of my marriage program or the parish, like, you know, the moment you find out you're pregnant, like, consecrate, surrender. call upon the intercession of the mother of God, then whatever the saints you want to name your child, because that is something that offered to us. So the same thing is, so the term, the title, Holy Protection of the Mother of God or... In Slavonic, it's just pokrov, which just means protection, or in Greek, skepi, which means protection too. But both in the Greek and the Slavonic, that word pokrov or skepi, that means protection, also implies protection either from a veil or a cloak or a shroud or something. So there's the image here. I mean, I think it's very similar to Matthew and Luke, Matthew 23 and Luke 13, where Jesus is mourning over the city of Jerusalem. And he says, Jerusalem, Jerusalem, the city that kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to it. How often have I desired to gather your children together like a hen gathers her brood under her wings, but you are not willing. So when we think of protection, I mean, imagine being in a really anxious situation. Imagine being attacked. Jesus compares, there's something about drawing you close and protecting you with a garment or with a wing or something like that that I imagine if you're afraid you're going to die, you're kind of looking for some sort of a shield in that way, and that's what protection or a cloak or shroud means, means the same thing. But the title that we have, the Feast, the Feast of the Holy Protection of the Mother of God is on October 1st, and then the... The feast comes from an event, a real event in the year 9-11, an easy year to remember. At that time, the Slavs were barbarians, and they actually had their conversion shortly after with Vladimir, but the Slavs were barbarians, and they were attacking Constantinople. And in the attack, when they were attacking, the people gathered in one church of Lechernaya. I've actually been there. There's a well there. It's this beautiful, beautiful, newer church, but in now Istanbul. And what happened was, is the people. They were gathered there, and while the city was being attacked by these Slav barbarians, they were gathered in church, and they were praying to the Mother of God because they had that exact same feeling. The idea of a mother—quick side note—I think there's something beautiful about the—we just celebrated remission of the assumption of the Mother of God. There's something beautiful about the fact that God desired His mother and our mother. She desired her body to be in heaven. I mean, the whole point of the assumption was that her body was a temple and it was supposed to remain pure. It was not supposed to be corrupted. So she brought that temple to heaven so that it remained incorrupt forever from her conception up until her assumption in heaven. But there's something beautiful about how dependent we are upon our mother's bodies. We grow inside of our mother's bodies. We're comforted by our mother's bodies. There's something about the physical nature of a mother when we're young that is so important. And then God said, waiting for you in heaven is your mother. and she has a body.
